Down syndrome is the most common chromosomal disorder, associated with moderate 
to severe intellectual disability. While life expectancy of Down syndrome 
population has greatly increased over the last decades, mortality rates are 
still high and subjects are facing prematurely a phenomenon of atypical and 
accelerated aging. The presence of an immune impairment in Down syndrome 
subjects is suggested for a long time by the existence of an increased incidence 
of infections, the incomplete efficacy of vaccinations, and a high prevalence of 
autoimmunity. Immunologic abnormalities have been described since many years in 
this population, both from a numerical and a functional points of view, and 
these abnormalities can mirror the ones observed during normal aging. In this 
review, we summarize our knowledge on immunologic disturbances commonly observed 
in subjects with Down syndrome, and in innate and adaptive immunity, as well as 
regarding chronic inflammation. We then discuss the role of accelerated aging in 
these observed abnormalities and finally review the potential age-associated 
molecular and cellular mechanisms involved.

