Pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH) is a devastating disease of the 
cardiopulmonary system caused by the narrowing of the pulmonary arteries, 
leading to increased vascular resistance and pressure. This leads to right 
ventricle remodeling, dysfunction, and eventually, death. While conventional 
therapies have largely focused on targeting vasodilation, other pathological 
features of PAH including aberrant inflammation, mitochondrial dynamics, cell 
proliferation, and migration have not been well explored. Thus, despite some 
recent improvements in PAH treatment, the life expectancy and quality of life 
